From Function to Hypergraph

We introduce the Fourier transform and Laplacian in the Section Preliminaries. Note that

Moreover, review that , indicating that the Laplacian is identical to the Laplacian matrix in terms of graph. Thus, to act convolution on the graph, we should find the similar role to that of , i.e., the eigenvectors of , and the Property 2 tells us it is feasible to find the matrix consisting linearly independent eigenvectors.
Specifically, the eigenvector of Laplacian matrix act as the base of Fourier transform and eigenvalue as the frequency. To understand it, we can carefully think the connection between them. On the one hand, the Fourier transform decompose a function into a linear combination of trigonometric functions, while the graph Fourier transform decompose the into the linear combination of eigenvectors of Laplacian matrix; on the other hand, based on , the eigenvalue denotes the weight of an eigenvector (i.e., the less eigenvalue is, the less important the eigenvector is), acting as the frequency of transform.
